            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/49590",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ultra_blue",
                        "name": "ultra_blue",
                        "displayName": "Greg Gomez",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Added some formatting to make it easier to read.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ultra_blue",
                        "name": "ultra_blue",
                        "displayName": "Greg Gomez",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2012-01-31T01:30:33.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2012-01-31T01:30:33.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/49717",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=adamlundrigan",
                        "name": "adamlundrigan",
                        "displayName": "Adam Lundrigan",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Zend_Date::set does not understand passing that format of date as the first argument.  It's primarily used to set components of dates, and if the second argument is omitted it assumes the first is a timestamp.  To create a date object with the format you use in your example, you'll need to do this:\r\n{code}\r\nfunction convertDate($date) {\r\n    $zDate = new Zend_Date($date, 'yyyy-MMM-dd HH:mm');\r\n    return $zDate->get(Zend_Date::W3C);\r\n}   \r\n{code}\r\nOf course, if you want the dates passed in to be UTC, you'll need to use {{date_default_timezone_set}} beforehand.  Changing the timezone on the Zend_Db object will offset the time stored in that object from the server's local time to UTC. \r\n\r\nWhen I run the above function (in my local timezone) using your examples I get this:\r\n{code}\r\nphp> echo convertDate('2012-May-01 01:50');\r\n2012-05-01T01:50:00-02:30\r\nphp> echo convertDate('2012-Jun-01 23:26');\r\n2012-06-01T23:26:00-02:30\r\nphp> echo convertDate('2012-Jan-04 02:59');\r\n2012-01-04T02:59:00-03:30\r\n{code}\r\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=adamlundrigan",
                        "name": "adamlundrigan",
                        "displayName": "Adam Lundrigan",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2012-02-23T23:05:36.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2012-02-23T23:05:36.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/49725",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ultra_blue",
                        "name": "ultra_blue",
                        "displayName": "Greg Gomez",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Hi, Adam:\r\n\r\nThanks so much for your reply -- it's crystal clear now. And it's in the docs, as well -- I'm not sure why I thought I could get away with a date\/time in an arbitrary format as I was attempting to do.\r\n\r\nThanks again!\r\nGreg",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ultra_blue",
                        "name": "ultra_blue",
                        "displayName": "Greg Gomez",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2012-02-24T00:25:45.000+0000",
